Artur Davis not only voted against Obamacare, but he voted with the corporate Republicans the vast majority of the time, even though he was a Democrat representing Alabama Congressional District 7, which included the Black Belt.

What Artur Davis tried to do to the Democratic Party's major issues, and the first Black President of the US, in a failed attempt get elected Governor of Alabama, demonstrated his basic flaws in his character! After Davis had receive total support from President and Mrs. Obama and 90% of the Democrats in Alabama, he voted against the President's signature issue, "Obamacare." If his vote had prevailed, it would have had ramifications for generations to come. Not only would it have resulted in the death of 562 poor people a year in the state of Alabama, but it may have resulted in a failed Presidency of the first Black President. The image would have eroded the hopes, dreams, confidence and aspirations of young Black boys and girls for generations in America.

After the President‚Äôs Health Care Plan was approved by one vote, and the Democrats solidly rejected Artur Davis‚Äô bid for Governor, Artur Davis still on his mission to destroy President Obama and the Party, went to the Republican National Convention. He boldly declared his support for Mitt Romney for President in an effort to ensure President Obama would go down in history as a failed Presidency! Artur Davis failed again because of the same reason, lack of integrity. After the Republicans discorded him like a used condom, he returned to Montgomery to continue his deceit by attempting to con the people again in the Mayoral Race. WE MUST AGAIN SHOW HIM THE ROAD

ad_creative_body:
Metro Denver Economic Equity Project (Metro DEEP) is a community-lead initiative facilitated by Diversity Dynamics to create unity around economic development projects that positively serve the Denver Metro Area African-American community with a goal of creating a lasting ecosystem of Black (includes the entire African Diaspora in Metro Denver) economic ownership.

On the 4th Friday of the month, Diversity Dynamics is facilitating a 6-month series of conversations to co-create our community driven strategic plan for equity.  Your engagement will help finalize our infrastructure and create opportunities that lead to ownership of our economy in Metro Denver.  The engagement of Faith, Civic, Business, Non-profit, Entertainment, Community and Urban Influencers like you will ensure we get this collective economic initiative right.

Each meeting will have complementary wine, hors d'oeuvres, networking and special offers. 

Please come ready to share your ideas and voice and fellowship with diverse community champions. 

August 23rd - Overview & Vision - Ownership of Our Economy + Real Estate w/Haroun Cowans and Albus Brooks

September 27th -  Setting Ownership Foundations + Cannibus

October 25th - Building Stakeholders for Ownership + Construction

November 22nd- Cementing Policy for Ownership + Procurement

December 13th - Building Infastructure for Ownership + Entertainment

January 24th - Building Systems for Ownership + Athletics

See the Years of History in the Month of August.

‚ÄúYou have a conversation piece of the past. Keep history alive.‚Äù 
Just Wear It, You Empower Others. 

www.sagainnumbers.com

Did you know?

1619

August 20. Twenty Africans arrived in Jamestown, Virginia, aboard a Dutch ship. They were the first blacks to be forcibly settled as involuntary laborers in the North American British Colonies.

1797

August 30. A slave revolt near Richmond, Virginia, led by Gabriel Prosser and Jack Bowley, was first postponed and then betrayed. More than 40 blacks were eventually executed.

1818

August 18. General Andrew Jackson defeated a force of Native Americans and African-Americans to end the First Seminole War.

1831

August 21-22. The Nat Turner revolt ran its course in Southampton County, Virginia.

1861

August 23. James Stone of Ohio enlisted to become the first black to fight for the Union during the Civil War. He was very light skinned and was married to a white woman. His racial identity was revealed after his death in 1862.

1920

August 1-2. The national convention of Marcus Garvey's Universal Negro Improvement Society met in New York City. Garvey would be charged with mail fraud in 1923. He was convicted in 1925 and deported in 1927 after serving time in prison.

1936

August 9. Jesse Owens won four gold medals at the Summer Olympics in Berlin.

1957

August 29. Congress passed the Voting Rights Bill of 1957, the first major civil rights legislation in more than 75 years.

1963

August 28. The March on Washington was the largest civil rights demonstration ever. Martin Luther King, Jr., delivered his "I Have a Dream" speech.

1965

August 11-21. The Watts riots left 34 dead, more than 3,500 arrested, and property damage of about 225 million dollars.

1970

August 7. There was a shootout during an attempted escape in a San Rafael, California, courthouse. Implicated in the incident, Angela Davis went into hiding to avoid arrest. Davis would be acquitted of all charges on June 4, 1972.

1983

August 30. Guion (Guy) S. Bluford, Jr. was the first black American astronaut to make a space flight on board the space shuttle Challenger

1992

August 3. Jackie Joyner-Kersee was the first woman to repeat as Olympic heptathlon champion.

The people of our neighborhoods want an open, televised debate on how to strengthen Hartford‚Äôs schools, clean up our neighborhoods, and create good paying jobs for our residents. Bronin clearly doesn‚Äôt want to debate candidates with deep Hartford roots again because we will continue to show just how out of touch he is with the people of our neighborhoods.

WE KNOW he only shows up in our neighborhoods during campaign season, and it is unacceptable that Bronin won‚Äôt answer questions about his failed record of closing schools and libraries (and even a park!). 

Why did he raise taxes on Hartford homeowners two years in a row but give away tens of millions to his campaign donors?

WHY THE BATTLE BETWEEN LAW ENFORCEMENT, BORDER PATROL AND DRUG TRAFFICKERS IS NOW MORE OF AN ARMS RACE THAN EVER BEFORE IN OUR HISTORY.  IT'S THE ARRIVAL OF SYNTHETIC DRUGS THAT HAS CHANGED DRUG TRAFFICKING FOREVER.

The New World of Synthetic Drugs Has Changed Drug Trafficking Forever.  

Synthetic man-made highs could dissolve the border issues and transform the global drug trade.  These man-made highs include well-known banned substances such as methamphetamine, MDMA, LSD, and ketamine; a vast array of new psychoactive substances (NPS) including cathinones and synthetic cannabinoids; black market medicines such as fentanyl and tranquilizers, and dangerous or impure analogues and substitutes of the above.

WHY?  THEY CAN BE MADE ANYWHERE CHEAPER FOR MORE PROFIT

Manufactured anywhere, from DIY bathroom labs to huge chemical factories, synthetic drugs are cheaper and easier to make than cocaine and heroin because there is no reliance on the cultivation of plants. Factories can pivot from making one drug to another‚Äîincluding the legal precursor chemicals used in banned substances‚Äîin days, quickly adapting to market demand. Because of the way they are produced and trafficked, they can be made, shipped and consumed in a relative instant and are more affordable for both suppliers and customers.

Thomas Pietschmann, a drug trend analyst at the U.N.‚Äôs Office of Drugs and Crime, said ‚Äúthe most marked increase in the drugs seized over the past two decades has clearly been in synthetic drugs.‚Äù He added that while the global popularity of cannabis means that plant-based drugs are still way more prevalent than synthetics, seizures of lab-formed substances have skyrocketed compared with drugs derived from plants.

Peter Andreas, a professor of international studies at Brown University and the author of Border Games: Policing the U.S.-Mexico Divide, put it more simply: ‚ÄúThe future is synthetic.‚Äù Andreas said this will have all sorts of repercussions for border controls.

Weekly Bellaire Crime Report

YES, there is crime in Bellaire.  We need more police patrolling the streets.

Aug. 5

  At 1:55 p.m., Officer Trujillo was dispatched to 4300 Edith St. in reference to a burglary of a motor vehicle. Upon arrival he spoke to the victim who stated an unknown person(s) broke into her vehicle and stole her purse.

  At 10:30 a.m., Officer Jenkins was dispatched to the 5400 block of Braeburn Dr. concerning theft of lawn equipment. A black BMW with four suspects stopped by the owner‚Äôs trailer and stole a blower and tiller.

Aug. 6

  At 4:10 p.m., Officer Carson was dispatched to the 4300 block of Cynthia Street in regards a package taken from her front porch. A white male was observed taking the package on July 30, 2019 at approximately 2200 hours.

  At 4:33 p.m., Officer Clisham arrived at the 5200 block of Valerie Street in reference to a firearm being stolen out of the reportee‚Äôs vehicle. After further investigation it is believed the firearm was removed from the vehicle outside the city limits of Bellaire. Officer Clisham completed a theft report to expedite the firearm being entered into NCIC as stolen.

  At 1:40 p.m., Officers Lysack, Lopez, and Jenkins were dispatched to the 4800 block of Holt Street in reference to a burglary of a habitation. Officers arrived on scene and met with the victim who stated an unknown suspect broke the window in the rear door of the house to gain entry. At the time of this report nothing has been discovered to be missing. Two black males were seen entering the back yard after exiting a silver 4 door car with chrome rims and paper license plate.

Aug. 7

  At 12:20 a.m., Officers responded to the 5200 block of IH 610 WLS S/B in reference to multiple vehicles racing on the highway. Officers Barrientos and Baylis conducted a traffic stop on a white Chevrolet Camaro. The driver was arrested for the charge of racing on the highway.

  At 4:20 p.m., Officer Carson was dispatched to 5233 Bellaire Blvd. in reference to a theft from an employee.

  At 3:33 p.m., Officers responded to 5859 Bissonnet St. in reference to an assault in progress. After arriving on location and further investigation, it was found the suspect in this case had assaulted a clerk, causing bodily injury, and attempted to steal a cell phone and flee the scene. Said suspect was placed into custody on scene and is charged with robbery with bodily injury.

  At 7:45 p.m., Officer Trujillo was dispatched to the 5200 block of Woodlawn Place in reference to a theft of a motor vehicle. Upon arrival he spoke to the victim who stated sometime on today‚Äôs date an unknown person(s) took his vehicle without his permission.

  At 6:31 p.m., Officer Andrade was dispatched to the Bellaire Police Department in reference to an assault that occurred at 4545 Bissonnet St. Upon arrival, Officer Andrade made contact with the victim who stated he was assaulted by his estranged spouse during child visitation.

  At 10 p.m., Officer Carson was dispatched to 5107 Bellaire Blvd. in reference to a burglary of a motor vehicle. The unknown suspect(s) broke the victim‚Äôs right rear window stealing her purse.

Aug. 9

  At 5:46 p.m., Officer D. Norman was dispatched to a burglary of a motor vehicle in the 4600 block of Breaburn Drive. Officer Norman made contact with the victim who advised a black male, wearing all black, entered her unlocked vehicle on the passenger side and stole her purse from the front passenger seat.

  At 3:38 a.m., Officer Liccketto was patrolling the 8000 block of the West Loop East Service Road and observed a vehicle fail to maintain a single marked lane. Officer Liccketto conducted a traffic stop on the vehicle. During the investigation, the driver was found to be driving while intoxicated and taken into custody. Officer Guerra assisted with the case.

  At 11:16 p.m., Officer Ortega was on patrol in the 7500 block of Chimney Rock Road and observed a vehicle traveling northbound in the 7500 block of Chimney Rock Road with an improperly displayed rear license plate. Officer Ortega made contact with the vehicle and upon further investigation, the driver was placed into custody for driving while intoxicated 2nd.

Aug. 10

  At 2:43 a.m., Officers conducted a traffic stop at the 6700 block of West Loop South The driver was arrested for driving while intoxicated.

  At 7:35 a.m., Officer Liccketto was dispatched to the 6000 block of the West Loop in reference to a burglary of a vehicle. The victim ran out of gas on the highway and walked to a gas station to fill up his gas can. During the time he was gone, an unknown suspect parked their vehicle behind his and took a sprayer from his bed of his truck. The victim was able to take pictures of the suspect as they were driving away.

Aug. 11

  At 7:54 p.m., Officer Schwausch was dispatched to a DWI in progress traveling within the city limits of the City of Bellaire. Officer Schwausch found the vehicle at the 6300 block of South Rice Ave. Officer Schwausch initiated a traffic stop on the suspect vehicle. Further investigation found the driver to be driving while intoxicated. The suspect was charged with driving while intoxicated/open container and placed into custody without incident. Bellaire Police Officer Barrientos assisted with Spanish translation in this investigation.

  At 4:53 a.m., Corporal Clawson and Officer Ortega observed two vehicles honking before one of them cut the other off in the 5100 block of Bissonnet Street. Corporal Clawson and Officer Ortega initiated traffic stops on the vehicles believing they were involved in a road rage incident. Further investigation found both drivers to be intoxicated (both over double the limit) and one of the drivers was also in possession of a controlled substance. Both were transported to the Bellaire Jail and processed without incident.

  At 10 p.m., an unknown suspect gained entry, without using force, went into the cashier room at 4500 Evergreen St. and removed cash from the safe after using the code to unlock it. The suspect then left the location in an unknown direction of travel.

  At 6:40 a.m., Officer Marcotte initiated a traffic stop on a 2008 Mitsubishi for displaying invalid registration in the 5000 block of Evergreen Street. Anthony Scaramucci Reveals The Last Straw
William Southold | Opinion Columnist |The Southold Report
‚ÄúSpeaking fiction to power one story at a time.‚Äù
Veritas Per Ficta!

Donald Trump attacked Anthony Scaramucci (again) on Twitter this morning, just as I was finishing this story you are reading now. I had tracked Scaramucci down this weekend at Tate‚Äôs Bake Shop in Southampton. I had gotten the word that he was crazy for their in season, fresh picked raspberry scones, and why wouldn‚Äôt he be, I was chowing down on one when I saw him come through the door.

I gave him time to make his order and sit down before I approached him, and asked for a word. He took one look at his phone and shut it down before he looked up and said, ‚ÄúSure, have a seat. I know you.‚Äù

I don‚Äôt know which surprised me more, the fact that he knew me, or the fact that he graciously allowed me to join him. It was early, and we were the only two seated on the far side, furthest from the counter.

‚ÄúI know you,‚Äù he repeated, ‚ÄúI‚Äôve seen you around D.C. Tell me your name again.‚Äù

I did, and he responded, ‚ÄúOh, yeah, the Fake News guy.‚Äù

‚ÄúNone other."

‚ÄúHey, you know I was once a Fake HouseGuest on Celebrity Big Brother 2.‚Äù

‚ÄúCelebrity Big Brother . . .?‚Äù

‚ÄúA show I was on once. It was a blast. You didn‚Äôt see it. That‚Äôs OK. So what can I do for you Mr. Fake News Guy?‚Äù

‚ÄúWell,‚Äù I said, trying to get right to it, ‚Äúyou‚Äôve been all over the news lately, encouraging people . . .‚Äù

‚ÄúTo think for themselves‚Äù he cut me off. ‚ÄúWe are in a terrible fix, our country of ours, and we need to do something about it. Quickly. Bigly, as my old but briefest of bosses might have said it.‚Äù

He sounded hopped up on coffee, but there was no food or drink in front of him.

‚ÄúI‚Äôve heard you‚Äôre working with Bill Kristol, to come up with a challenger to your once brief boss,‚Äù I said.

Just then the waitress brought his order over. Yep, raspberry scone. Nailed it!

‚ÄúThank you, Margaret. Looks great,‚Äù he told her.

‚ÄúAlways is,‚Äù she said, and turned and left.

‚ÄúYou know, it‚Äôs always important to thank your service people, by name. By name,‚Äù he repeated. They don‚Äôt always stay as waitresses, or whatever. People need recognition! They need to know when they are doing their job well.  That's how you get better service.  Now, what were we talking about? I gotta tell ya, I come in here to work, so . . .‚Äù hands extended, palms up, phone at the ready, with a little shrug.

I took it as intended, to bring our brief conversation to an end.

‚ÄúSo any comment on Kristol?‚Äù I asked him, making ready to get up.

‚ÄúSomething‚Äôs gotta be done, I can tell you that, and Kristol‚Äôs a man who can pull it all together.

He paused a moment, in thought. ‚ÄúYou know, everybody thought I got fired because of my profanity laced tirade. The truth is, I wanted out. Do you know what was the last thing Trump asked me to do?‚Äù

‚ÄúYou mean before you . . . left as Communication Director?

‚ÄúYeah. The big guy could tell things were goin‚Äô south with his Black Outreach‚Äù he liked to call it. He calls me into the Oval, and shows me this gold plated statue he had made. Says right on it, World‚Äôs Least Racist Person EVER!.

‚ÄúHe had a statue of himself, World‚Äôs Least Racist . . . ‚Äú

‚ÄúYeah, you got it. He told me I had to find a Black celebrity, he wanted Iron Mike, or Dennis Rodman, or Kanye, that‚Äôs who he really wanted. He told me to find one of them, and tell them to present him with this statue. Like it was their idea.‚Äù

‚ÄúThat‚Äôs a little . . . bold.‚Äù

‚ÄúYa think? It‚Äôs bull goose looney! I said Boss, he used to like me to call him Boss, I said you can‚Äôt ask someone else to lie for you. You gotta go at it straight. There must be plenty of celebs willing to come out for you over racism. And he says, no, this is the way. It‚Äôs gotta be big. We can do the whole thing in the Rose Garden, it‚Äôs gotta be the gold plated statue.‚Äù

‚ÄúI say, but it‚Äôs all a big lie you‚Äôre trying to pull off, you want someone to go on the record with your lie, and he says, Mooch, you know it‚Äôs my way or the highway around here. You get that much don‚Äôt you?‚Äù

‚ÄúThat was his response?‚Äù

‚ÄúThe Big Lie, the bigger the better. People need to stop putting up with it. I called him on it. He doesn‚Äôt like that one bit. Next thing I know, I got canned.‚Äù

‚ÄúSo, can I quote you on this?‚Äù

‚ÄúSure. Quote me all you want. People need to know this stuff. It‚Äôs time to pull the plug on this nut job.‚Äù

I left Mr. Scaramucci to his coffee and scone, and was working on this story when Trump unleashed his latest attack dog tweet on the Mooch. So, that‚Äôs the story at this hour. It‚Äôs bound to change, though. It‚Äôs about Trump.

It's World Humanitarian Day AND #MemberMonday ‚Äî Clara Luper seemed like the obvious fit. 

During her 41 years as an award-winning Oklahoma educator, Luper taught history and made history. She grew up in Okfuskee County (near Hoffman) and went on to receive her Bachelor of Arts degree from Langston University and her master's degree from The University of Oklahoma. 

Luper is known as the mother of the civil rights movement. In 1958, she coordinated the first publicized sit-in in the nation at the Katz Drug Store lunch counter in Oklahoma City. Thanks to her persistence and patience, Katz desegregated the lunch counters in each of its 38 stores. 

"I knew I was right, because somewhere I read in the 14th Amendment that I was a citizen and I had rights, and I had the right to eat. Within that hamburger was the whole essence of democracy. If you could deny me the right to eat, you could deny me the right to live or work where I want." ‚Äî Clara Luper

This month is also the 50th anniversary of the OKC Sanitation Strike, where more than 200 Black sanitation workers went on strike, citing poor working conditions, pay and racist treatment. Luper was instrumental in leading this movement. 

Visit reveel.it/lp/s/pbpsg2 to learn more about Luper's life and accomplishments.

When her father became president in 1977, nine-year-old Amy Carter moved from her home in Georgia to the White House in the middle of the school year. She started at Thaddeus Stevens Elementary School, a few blocks from the White House, making her the first president‚Äôs child to attend a local public school since Quentin Roosevelt. 

Her new teacher, Verona Meeder, had just the thing to help ease Amy‚Äôs transition. Verona‚Äôs dog had given birth to a litter of puppies on the night Jimmy Carter was elected President of the United States. Because of their serendipitous birth, she promised one of the Border Collie mix puppies to Amy Carter and delivered him to the White House after her first day of school.

The black-and-white puppy was dubbed ‚ÄúGrits.‚Äù This was probably a play on the campaign slogan ‚ÄúGrits and Fritz in ‚Äô76,‚Äù which referred to President Carter‚Äôs southern roots and his running mate Walter Mondale‚Äôs nickname. 

Grits quickly became popular with both the first family and the press. Newspapers reported that Amy was ‚Äúecstatic‚Äù with her new friend. He joined her on sleepovers in her treehouse on the South Lawn. The nonprofit Voice for Animals Society officially dubbed him the ‚Äúfirst canine.‚Äù

Grits even got involved in a bit of charity work. Dr. Stephen Melman, a D.C.-area veterinarian, enlisted the first dog to help promote a heartworm prevention drive. They posed for photos on the South Lawn to encourage dog owners to take their pets for preventative screenings.

After two and a half years in the White House, Grits eventually returned to live with Mrs. Meeder, who had recently lost her own dog.

In this photograph, Amy Carter poses with Grits on the White House steps.

Credit: Jimmy Carter Presidential Library and Museum / NARA

This evening, I attended the unveiling of a historical marker here in Durham which honored the establishment of the Algonquin Tennis Club in 1922. This club was established during the days of segregation to give African American tennis enthusiasts a place to play a favorite sport as well as to socialize and strategize. The land for the club was purchased in 1934, and the building where the club was housed provided a dining room as well as guest rooms for black tourists visiting Durham. The club hosted tournaments and exhibition matches for Black athletes such as Althea Gibson and Arthur Ash, both of whom became recognized worldwide as accomplished tennis players. The club was also the place where Black political activists came together to establish the Durham Committee on the Affairs of Black People in 1935. The Durham Committee continues today to provide leadership in our community and to advocate for progressive values and equal opportunity for all. It was great to attend this beautiful ceremony. 
I‚Äôd like to thank Nathan Garrett and his wife Wanda for serving as the Master and Mistress of Ceremonies for this beautiful event. I would also like to recognize Secretary Susi Hamilton, who leads the NC Department of Cultural Resources, which oversees the historical monument program among her vast responsibilities.

* Fabric paint 
* Stencil brush
* Painter's tape
* Gloves (optional)
* Black and white buffalo plaid rug

‚úÖ Let‚Äôs Begin:

1. Arrange your stencil on the doormat using painter's tape to secure.
2. Use paint and stencil brush to paint inside the image. Wear gloves because you will need to use your fingers to hold down some sides!
3. Peel off the vinyl stencil right away to reveal the finished project. You don‚Äôt want to leave the stencil on there for very long otherwise the cardstock might stick to the mat. You can fill in any spots with a black sharpie or more paint with a small brush.
4. Let dry for 24-to-48 hours before placing outside (in case it rains ‚Äì fabric paint needs time to dry completely before becoming waterproof).

And in the workplace, Black and Brown women are disproportionately mistreated. In a recent survey, nearly two-thirds of Black and Latina women reported experiencing racial discrimination at work. Even though Black women and Latinas are often the leaders and decision-makers in their own homes and communities, they hold only one spot on the Fortune 500 CEO list and less than 5% of Fortune 500 Board positions. 

That‚Äôs why I have a new plan: a set of executive actions I will take on day one of the Warren administration to boost wages for women of color and open up new pathways to the leadership positions they deserve. I will deny contracting opportunities to companies with poor track records on diversity and equal pay. I will ban contractors from asking applicants for past salary information and criminal histories. And I will ensure that federal contractors must extend a $15 minimum wage and benefits (including paid family leave, fair scheduling, and collective bargaining rights) to all employees. 

It‚Äôs time for the government to value the work of women of color ‚Äî and boost our economy in the process.

ANDY TAGGART SPEAKS POTUS (VIDEO): So, yesterday we saw another instance of the media carrying out its own agenda  only this time it was from from Paul Gallo on his SuperTalk Mississippi radio show. I respect Paul, have a good relationship with Paul and have been on his show many times. (And I hope to do so in the future.) He brings much needed discourse to our political process.That said, Republicans like to accuse "the liberal media" of bias so isn't it only fair that when that bias shows up in "conservative media" they be called out, too? (And you wonder why the approval rating of the media is as low as Congress.) This is from the debate with Andy Taggart and Mark Baker which Ms. Fitch refused to appear in (even though it was re-arranged for her schedule). You get to see it in his own words and from his lips, not some edited 40 character tweet from 3 yrs ago summarized by a radio host. Ronald Reagan's 80/20 rule (voting w/ me 80% of the time as opposed to 100% means you're my friend not my enemy) is well known.  Reasonable people, ie, Mississippi voters, know that you don't see eye-to-eye on everything, even though the media establishment would have you believe otherwise. An Attorney General is required to apply the Constitution and the laws and must use independent judgement in carrying out the job.  Andy Taggart owns that fact.  Any lawyer worth his or her salt will tell you that fact. Why? Because the law, and life, are not black and white (or red and blue); step into a courtroom in our judicial system (set up by our Founders) and you will see this fact. And make no mistake, the AG must have those courtroom skills to represent you, me and every other Mississippian. I have faith, as I am sure Andy Taggart does, that the voters know when they are being played and when they aren't. So, take a look. Make up your own mind.

BOSTON HERALD CALLS OUT WARREN FOR ‚ÄòDANGEROUS AND FALSE RHETORIC‚Äô AGAINST POLICE, PAINTING LAW ENFORCEMENT AS CORRUPT AND RACIST.  

The editors of the Boston Herald are calling on 2020 Democrat presidential candidate Sen. Elizabeth Warren (D-MA) to ‚Äústop using dangerous and false‚Äù rhetoric regarding law enforcement officers.  ‚ÄúLaw enforcement is under assault in this country,‚Äù wrote the Herald‚Äôs editorial board. ‚ÄúSeveral ICE facilities have been attacked this year. On Wednesday, six Philadelphia police officers were shot in the line of duty during a standoff. Those same police also had to deal with being taunted by some bystanders, who laughed and yelled at them in the midst of the gunfire.‚Äù

The Boston Herald urged that Democratic presidential candidate Sen. Elizabeth Warren (D-Mass.) ‚Äúmust stop using dangerous and false rhetoric immediately,‚Äù against police by painting law enforcement as hopelessly corrupt and racist. The paper argued this puts police in danger and cited law enforcement officials concerned about Warren‚Äôs rhetoric.

The Herald also specifically flagged its hometown senator for a tweet perpetuating the falsehood that teenager Michael Brown was ‚Äúmurdered‚Äù by police in Ferguson, Mo., even though according to the investigation into Brown‚Äôs case released during the Obama administration, ‚ÄúThe unarmed 18-year-old black man‚Äôs shooting by a police officer was ruled an act of ‚Äòself-defense‚Äô by the U.S. Department of Justice. Witnesses corroborated the officer‚Äôs testimony that Brown was charging at him after already trying to wrestle away his gun,‚Äù the Herald wrote.

‚ÄúThe Massachusetts Chiefs of Police Association wrote to Warren Tuesday saying her Friday tweet that black teen Michael Brown of Ferguson, Mo., was  ‚Äòmurdered by a white police officer‚Äô is ‚Äòappalling,‚Äô‚Äù the Herald noted.

The Herald‚Äôs accuracy was in contrast to national media networks like MSNBC and CNN, which DID NOT not correct Warren‚Äôs statement.

Former George W. Bush White House spokesman Ari Fleischer, a prominent conservative, tweeted about the network silence, which was reported by The Washington Free Beacon: ‚ÄúMSNBC, CNN Ignore Warren and Harris Falsely Tweeting Michael Brown Was Murdered.‚Äù

    MSNBC, CNN Ignore Warren and Harris Falsely Tweeting Michael Brown Was Murdered https://t.co/gRJZqDmGZ0

    ‚Äî Ari Fleischer (@AriFleischer) August 13, 2019

The Herald noted that two Massachusetts police officers were murdered last year.

The Boston Herald editorial notes:

    Last year it was ICE she targeted for expulsion, saying that it should be replaced with ‚Äúsomething that reflects our morality.‚Äù She bellowed to a boisterous Boston City Hall Plaza crowd that, ‚ÄúThis is about children held in cages. This is about babies scattered all across this country.‚Äù [Emphasis added]

     Just days later, a Cambridge man offered to pay $500 to anyone who would kill an ICE agent. Law enforcement officers ‚Äî the same ones Warren derides routinely ‚Äî apprehended and charged the man. [Emphasis added]

‚ÄúOn Wednesday, six Philadelphia police officers were shot in the line of duty during a standoff,‚Äù The Boston Herald editors wrote. ‚ÄúThose same police also had to deal with being taunted by some bystanders, who laughed and yelled at them in the midst of the gunfire.‚Äù

Last year, police chiefs in Massachusetts denounced Warren for her comments at a predominantly black American college that police departments in the U.S. are racist.

‚ÄúLet‚Äôs just start with the hard truth about our criminal justice system,‚Äù Warren said in August 2018. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs racist. It is. And when I say our system, I mean all the way. I mean front to back.‚Äù

Since January, the Officer Down Memorial Page records that 73 law enforcement officers have died or been killed in the line of duty. Last year, more than 160 law enforcement officers died or were killed across the country.

The mission of Indiana Minority Health Coalition (IMHC) is to eliminate health disparities through research, education, advocacy, and working to increase access to health care services in minority communities. We know that we can‚Äôt do this alone. Once again, we are reaching to our partners around the state who address chronic disease conditions to join us for our 23rd Minority Health Initiative Annual Luncheon (MHIAL) on September 17, 2019, 11:00 am ‚Äì 1:30 pm at the Willows on Westfield, 6279 Westfield Blvd, Indianapolis, IN.
MHIAL 2019 Luncheon Theme
This year our theme is ‚ÄúBlack Maternal Mortality: Framing the Problem; Finding Solutions.‚Äù Indiana has one of the nation‚Äôs worst rates of mothers dying while pregnant or within a year after giving birth. About 41 women in Indiana die per every 100,000 live births, according to data from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. That rate is even worse for Black women. Some 53 Black Hoosier moms die for every 100,000 live births. That's on par with the maternal death rate in countries like Iraq and Vietnam, according to U.S. government statistics. A panel of experts will discuss both challenges and solutions and best practices being implemented. 
About the Minority Health Initiative Annual Luncheon (MHIAL)
MHIAL is Indiana‚Äôs largest activity held that focuses on how chronic disease, health disparities, and lack of affordable/accessible health care affect minorities.  MHIAL attracts approximately 300-500 attendees including representation from many of the state‚Äôs largest health care and insurance providers, state agencies, as well as, legislators and policy makers. There is also representation from IMHC‚Äôs 23 minority health coalitions from around the state.

Today we heard from many police chiefs, county DHS directors, hospital officials, and mental healthcare experts on just how important it is to open up more beds in our region for people having a mental health crisis. It could not be more clear that Governor Evers made a mistake when vetoing this funding.

From Superior and Ashland to Black River Falls and La Crosse, the current proposal would save taxpayers a minimum of $2.7 million, not to mention the human toll it takes on our officers and patients to make round trips to Winnebago or Mendota. With multiple upcoming opportunities to reinstate this funding, there is no reason for northern legislators, on both sides of the aisle, to not support this.
